{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_bradbury_ver01/data/sn92066979/00513687539/1911021401/0970.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nSENSATIONAL WIND-UP SALE\nIF YOU DON\u2019T WANT TO SAVE MONEY, IF YOU SIMPLY WON\u2019T BE SHOWN, IF YOU\u2019D JUST\nAS LEAVE PAY ANY OLD PRICE FOR YOUR MERCHANDISE, WE\u2019LL NOT EXPECT TO SEE YOU AT THIS SALE. IF THE OPPORTU\nNITY TO SAVE A FEW DOLLARS ON SEASONABLE MERCHANDISE APPEALS TO YOU, YOU'LL BE IN THE CROWD.\nWomen\u2019s and Children\u2019s Underwear\nWhen you have an opportunity like this to lay in a supply of Under\nwear at Wind-Up Sale prices, it would be an error of judgment not to\ntake advantage of this sale to supply your needs, if not for this season,\nfor next winter. On all vests and pants we are making a reduction of\nOne-Third\nWomen\u2019s Coats and Suits\nWe do not want to carry over a single Suit or Coat if we can help\nit and in order to sell the few rema ning numbers we are making a\nprice on all our Winter Coats and Suits of exactly\nOne-Half the Regular Price\nNOTES FROM THE COURT HOUSE.\nI\nThe hall at the court house is being\nrepapered today.\nThe treasurer\u2019s office will be given\nHtALIil\n$1.50\nPhysicians agree that an improperly\npurified blood supply has everything\nto do with the general health of the\nindividual. Unless you breathe prop\nel ly sufficient air is not taken into the\nlungs to revitalize your blood and con\nsequently it is an impossibility for the\nblood to repair the bodily waste in a\nproper manner.\nThe Rexali Shoulder Brace compels\nproper breathing in that it necessi- i\nta.es the weaier assuming a correct\nposition, thus assuring a sufficient\nquantity of air being taken into the i\nlungs to give new life to the blood.\nThis brace is light, cool, comfortable 1\n\u2014doesn\u2019t interfere with the circula-\nrion, and the wearer is unconscious of\nits presence except as an incorrect at\ntitude is assumed.\nBearing the highest endorsement of 1\nmedical authorities, we can unhesita 1\ningly recommend this brace to those 1\nwho need such an appliance with ev-\nery assurance that it will do all that is\n-claimed for it. 1\ni\nWe have the Rexali Shoulder Brace\nin all sizes. Price $1.50. Can be ob- f\ntallied only at our store\u2014The Rexali\nStore. f\nc\nMUI\u2019C UNIVERSITY BOOK\nrIILL J AN!) STORE!\nThe Rexali Store.\n\u2014_ 9 I\nI \u201cWHERE THE BETTER GOODS ARE.\u201d\nV 2 Price\nShirt Sale\na\nYou men wear a shirt every day.\nIt would be a big Item to you if you could get them at 2 price\n9 \u20142 shirts for price of one.\n,i Monday and Tuesday, 2 days only, you can do that at this store.\nTraveling man\u2019s samples.\nM Big lot men\u2019s soft collar shirts, sizes 15, 15'/ 2 16, 16J, 2 light I\n0 colors and dark; 40c to *2.25.\n3 These, almost ridiculous prices should cause you to anticipate\nst your needs 2 years ahead; carry away six or a dozen.\nJust notice our windows; more inside the store.\nfa Any shirt 2 price.\nOnly 2 days\u2014Monday and Tuesday.\nCLOTHING \u00abND\nI JLzIxH W SHOE COMPANY\nH 211 Second Street\u2014East side, under Walk-Over shoe man.\nMEYER RAIFE\nan overhauling, with new paper and 1\n1 paint.\nUnder Sheriff Still.ng has gone to 1\nthe country with papers in civil cases.\nGeorge Crumley was sent back to\nihe county jail today to await tiial be-;\nfore a jury in Justice Reids couit on 1\nthe Ibth foi assault and bat .ory.\nAll the offices were opened for busi\nness today, following their closing for\na holiday yesterday.\nJohn McCue filed a brand certificate\nwith the county clerk today.\nThe Laramie Development company\nsold to Gerhard Wessels, for $2,000,\nthe southwest quarter of the soutn\nwest quarter of section 26, township\n17, range' 76\u2018, in the Little Laramie\nvalley.\n'1 he Ernest Land and Cattle com\npany transferred to John W. Ernest,\nby warranty deed, for $1 and other\nconsiderations, all of section 13 and\n120 acres in section 12, township 17,\nrange 77.\nFred McLaughlin and wife sold to\nHans Olson, for S4O, right of way for\na ditch in township 13, range 76.\nEura and Cora Carmichael sold to\nL. N. Cleveland, for $4,800, eigh.y\nacres in section 16, township 18, range\n74.\nSheriff Frazer received a very hand\nsome valentine today, and at once fell\nto abusing a pretty young lady for\nhaving sent it to him. It was shown\nabout the court house and pronounced\na striking likeness, but the sheriff be\nlieves he Is even handsomer than the\npicture.\nThe pupils of the training school,!\nassisted by Miss Brown and the uni-,\nversify orchestra, will give their fifth\nannual patriotic program at Root\u2019s\nopera house Tuesday evening, Febru-\nary 21. Admission, twenty-five cents.\nSea s may be reserved without extra\ncharge at the Laramie Drug company\non Saturday.\nDallv Republican. 50c per month.\nTHE LARAMIE REPUBLICAN\u2014DAILY EDITION.\nMen\u2019s Underwear Bargains\nDon\u2019t you need something in the line of Underwear, Mr. Man?\nIf you do, now is the time to get it, as these prices will only be in force\nduring this sale and it will be your last opportunity of buying such good\nUnderwear at such reasonable prices.\nMen\u2019s Fleeced Cotton Underwear at\nMen\u2019s All-wool Underwear, worth $1.25, at. 90c\nMen\u2019s All-wool Underwear, worth $1.75, at $1.19\nMen\u2019s All-wool Underwear, worth $2.00, at ..$1.49\nMen\u2019s Clothing Special\nWe have qu tea number of Men s Suits left from the past sea\nson and we must sell these to make room for the new stock which is ar\nriving daily. Any Winter Suit in the line will be yours upon the pay\nment of\nless than the Regular Price\nPERSONAL PARAGRAPHS.\ni 1 Max Wolf of Chicago is in the city.\nN. E. Hulse of Alliance is in the\n1 city.\nI. V. Doak of Rock River is in Lar\namie.\nD. La\u00dfarre of Denver was here last\nnight.\nOra Haley left for Denver this\nmorning.\nC. E. Burns is in Laramie today from\nFoxpark.\nD. M. Wilt arrived horn Faxpark\nthis morning.\nA. T. Scoville was in from the ranch\nthis morning.\n1 E. Finesteln of New York If staying\nat the Kuster.\nA. J. Scraney of New York is visit\ning in Laramie.\nMiss Margaiet Bell returned to Den\nver this morning.\nOwen S. Case arrived from North\npark this morning.\n1 G. Schleseinger of San Francisco,\nis in town today.\nJ. M. Wilson of Foxpark is a Lara\nmie visitor today.\nOtto Gramm returned from Chey\nenne this afternoon.\nProf. Knight left for Cheyenne this\nmorning on business.\nR. M. Jamiscn left fcr Chejenne this I\nmorning on business.\nAlbert Nelson of Elk mountain spent\n1 the night in this city.\nMrs. H. C. Boston is in Laramie to\nday from Centennial.\nM. Cooling of Kansas City was a\nLaramie visitor today.\nMiss Daisy Smith left for Denxer\u2019\nthis morning on a visit.\nI A. F. Lindsey of Centennial arrived\nI in Laramie this morning.\nMr. and Mrs. Pat Cain will return to\nFoxpark in the morning.\nMr. and Mrs. Victor White returned\nto Rock River this afternoon.\nMis. R. M. Coen arrived in Laramie\nfrom Sherman this afternoon.\nMrs. R. P. Collins left for Cheyenne\nthis morning to visit relatives.\nAttorney S. C. Downey left for Rock\nRiver this afternoon on business.\nC. A. Shaw and wife and D. C. Culp\nof Denver were in the city today.\nC. V. Stansbury of Denver was reg\nistered at the Johnson last night i\nMrs. A. D. Chamberlin returned\nhome to Rock River this afternoon.\nM. Dooling, tTie railroad contractor,\ni eturned to Cheyehe this morning.\nRalph McCollough left this after\nnoon for Medicine Bow on business\nH. C. Fisher of San Francisco, ar\nrived in Laramie today, on business.\nMr. and Mrs. Ralph Johnson of the\nL. L. Laughlin ranch are in the city.\nI Judge Brown left for Cheyenne this\nmorning to appear before the supreme\ncourt.\nI Jake Herbst of Bosler was a busl\nness visitor to the county seat last\nnight.\nI James McGibbon came in from the\nWillow Creek ranch yesterday after\nnoon.\nHenry Kranz, a prominent farmer\nof Golden Prairie district near Chey-\nenne, died of Bright\u2019s disease yes\nterday, at St. John\u2019s hospital at Chey\nenne.\nRobert Gottschalff left this morn\ning for Denver to take treatment for\nhis eyes.\nEd Eykyn was in from his ranch\n;oday coming yesterday afternoon\nand spending the night here.\nW. Kelly of Pine Bluff, Wyo., was a\nbusiness visitor to the metropolis of\nthe Laramie valley last night.\nI Charles E. Woodard of Ti\u00a9 Siding\nwas a visitor to the county seat last\nnight, remaining over until today.\nFox as a Gamester.\nCharles James Fox, the English\nstatesman, was even more notorious in\nthe gaming world than he was famous\nin the world of politics. He had\nsquandered $250,000 before coming of\nage. He became one of the most profli\ngate gamesters of the vicious days in\nwhich he lived. Some of his finest dis\nplays In debate were sandwiched be\ntween excitement such as would un\nnerve most men who had no serious\nbusiness on band. Walpole has given\na glimpse of a typical passage in this\nextraordinary man\u2019s life. He had to\ntake part in the discussion on the\nthirty-nine articles in parliament on a\ncertain Thursday. He had sat up play\ning hazard from Tuesday evening until\n5 o\u2019clock on Wednesday afternoon. An\nhour before he had recovered SOO,OOO\nthat he had lost and by dinner time,\nwhich was 5 o\u2019clock, ended losing $55,-\n000. On Thursday he spoke In the\ndebate, went to dinner at past 11 at\nnight; thence to a club, where he\ndrank till 7 the next morning: thence\nto a gambling house, where he won\n$30,000, and between 3 and 1 in the\nafternoon he set out on a journey to\nNewmarket.\nPirates and Strategy.\nThe virtuous Island of Sark was not\nalways so. When Edward 111. was\nking, Sark was a haunt of pirates and\nwreckers. Sir A. Conan Doyle in \u201cSir\nNigel\u201d tells how they lived not upon\nthe Island, \u201cbut from what they can\ngather upon the sea around it. They\nare broken folk from all countries\njustice fliers, prison breakers, reavers,\nescaped bondsmen, murderers and\nstaff breakers who have made their\nway to this out In nd place and hold it\nagainst all comers.\u201d The merchants\nof Rye and Winchelsea fitted out an\nexpedition against those scourges of\nthe narrow seas. A landing was ob- 1\ntained by strategy. Leave was ob- 1\ntained to bury a supposititious dead\nsailor on the-island, the burying party)\nto come unarmed. But that apparent\ncoffin was filled with weapons, and so\nwas Sark cleansed of its evil inhabit- f\nants.\u2014London Standard.\nA Story of Mathews.\nCharles Mathews one day previous\nto the period of his publicly proclaimed\ndire bankruptcy invited a friend to\ndine with him. The walnuts were\nwashed down by some rare sherry.\n\u201cThat\u2019s a delicious wine/* his friend\nexclaimed. \u201cIt must have cost you a\nlot of money.\u201d\n\u201cIt didn\u2019t cost me anything that I\nknow of,\u201d the flighty comedian an\nswered, with a shrug.\n\u201cYou had It given to you. then?\u201d the\nfriend suggested.\n\u201cOh, no.\" answered Mathews; \u201cI\nbought It from Ellis, in Bond street.\u201d\n\u201cBut he will charge you something\nfor It?\u201d the friend exclaimed in aston\nishment.\n\u2018\u2018l believe he does write something\ndown in a book/* Charles retorted\ngravely. \u201cLet\u2019s have another glass,\nmy boy.\u201d j\nDaily republican 5U cent* a moacM\nYour New Spring Suit\nIs Waiting For You\nJust the exact shade, just the exact texture, just the exact\nweave you have pictured in your mind for your Spring suit or over\ncoat.\n\u2014lt\u2019s here!\n\u2014And priced exactly as you want it priced\u2014the sum you have\nfigured on paying.\nThat\u2019s the wonderful feature of The Royal Tailors\u2019 service. They\nseem to read Into every man\u2019s mind and anticipate every man\u2019s taste.\nThey have the happy faculty of having ready for you the pattern you\nlike\u2014without the need of having you ask them for it.\nThe biggest Spring line of attractive woolens ever in this town\nit\u2019s ready for you to look at In this store now.\nTHE COBDINER STORE\nLocal Agents for The Royol Talors.\nHEADING FOR\nGREA\u00a3WEST\nj HIGHER OFFICIALS OF UNION PA\nCIFIC EXPECTED TO MAKE\nINSPECTION TRIP.\nAt Ogden They Will Order Double\nTracking of Line East of That\nCity Through Weber Canon\u2014\nFreight Congestion of Few Years\nAgo Due to Inadequate Trackage.\nPresident Lovett, Vice President\nKrultschniU and other high officials\nof the Harriman lines are expected in\nOgden the coming week to decide on\nthe improvements most urgently de\nmanded by the Union Pacific and\nSouthern Pacific in and around Ogden,\nand, it is confidently asserted, that, as\na result of the visit, the first of the\ndouble trackage of the Union Pacific\nwill be from Ogden east through Web\ner canon.\nNeed of Second Line.\nJames J. Hill, at the time of the\nfreight congestion in 1906-7, confessed I\nthat the railroads of the United States\nwere years behind the traffic require-1\nments. If that were true then, what\nwill be the degree of inefficiency of the\nrailroads when, in the natural course\nof events, the country, regaining its\nequilibrium, begins to tax mine and 1\nfactory and farm to capacity to meet\nthe wants of a nation of\u201dover 92,000,-\n000 people?\nA Wise Decision.\nThe Harriman executive committee\nIs acting wisely in beginning this early,\nyet opportunely, to escape the culpa\nbility that must attach to other rail\nroad managers when through failure\nto Improve their lines In a period of\ncomparative inactivity they shall find\nwith a return of prosperity their trans\nportation facilities to be wholly in\nadequate? That reasoning has led\nlocal railroad men to affirm that not\nonly will the Union Pacific and South\nern Pacific be double-tracked before\nthe opening of the world\u2019s fair, but\nthe work of improving will begin im\nmediately and be rushed to complete\nas soon as possible.\nWill Be Made Manager Here.\nAs Intimated in The Republican a\nfew days ago, C. L. Carlson of Chey\nenne, at present an operator in the of\nfice at that place, will be made mana\nger of the Laramie office of the West\nern Union, taking the place made va\ncant by the resignation of Did Smith,\nand which has been held temporarily\nby Mr. Bridgeman. The latter will re\nturn to the office here as an operator,\nrelieving Mr. Somerville, who will\ntake the night shift at the ttaln order\ninstruments. Mr. Carlson will be here\nnext week.\nGone to Denver for Treatment.\nRobert Gottschalk, a machinist at\nthe shops, went to Denyer today for\ntreatment for one of his eyes. A few\ndays ago, while at work on the forward\npart of a boiler, he received a bit of\nlime Incrustation in one of his eyes. The\nlime caused little trouble at first, but\nIt has been growing more painful, and\nMr. Gottschalk will submit the eye\nto the surgeons at the hospital In Den\nver.\nTemperature Over District.\nThe maximum and minimum tem-\nTHERE IS ONE, WHY\nTo be sure of always getting your Groceries fresh. That way ia to\nbuy here.\n\u201cTHE BEST THE GROCER CAN DELIVER\nSMITH HHRVE.Y\nTHE QUICK GROCERS.\n210 Second Street. Phone 34 Red.\nTUESDAY, FEBRUARY 14, 1311.\nperature at Laramie yesterday and last\nnight were 38 and 17, with 31 and 15\nat Rawlins. The temperature at Lar\namie at 3 a. m. wag 21 and at Raw\nlins 19. A light snow fell from Lar\namie to Rawlins last nigtb, with leas\nthan an inch i- depth\n\nActing Agent at Rawlins.\nRoy Collins, night agent for the\nAmerican Express office at this place,\nhas gone to Rawlins as acting agent for\nthe company there. His friends hope\nthe place will he made permanent for\nhim.\nHere With Air Car.\nDan Brees, In charge of the air car\n.or the Hariman lines, is in the city to\nday, hia car being In the yards for a\nweek of examination of employes of\nthe road.\nThe January Payroll.\nThe January payroll for the ta\nployes of the Laramie Plilns line is\nbeing prepared by Auditor Woods and\nthe checks will be sent out later in the\nweek.\nTrain Annulled.\nTrain No. 18, which was wrecked ou\nthe Oregon Short Line last Bight, la\nI which the engineer and fireman were\nkilled, was annulled today.\nMore Ice to North Platte.\nThirty-six cars of Laramie river ice\nwere sent to North Platte this mom\nCLASS PINS.\nWe have just received a new ship\nment of Laramie High School enamel\ned Pennant Class Pins in red and\nwhite. E. D. Carter, the Jeweler. 159t2\nCertificate of Publication.\nInsurance Commissioner\u2019s Office,\nState of Wyoming, Cheyenne, Wyo.,\nFebruary 6th, 1911.\nIt Is hereby certified that the New\nHampsnire Fire Insurance Company\nof Manchester, in the State of New\nHampshire, has complied with the in\nsurance laws of this state and is auth\norized to transact the business of fire\ninsurance In this state tor the current\nyear.\nWitness my hand and seal of office\nthe day and year first above written.\n(Seal) R. B. FORSYTH,\nAuditor and Ex-Officio Insurance\nCommissioner.\nBy JOHN SCHUNEMAN, Deputy.\nE. A. WILKINSON, Agent.\nAsk for Solitaire canned goods, ts\nYou may turn into money anything\nof value through Republlcan\u201cWANT\u201d\nadvertising.\nWE ARE ANXIOUS\nthat we should be your family\njewelers, not only supplying\nyour larger wants, but every\nwant, large or small.\nE. GREENWOOD\nJeweler and Optician\nU. P. Watch Inspector,\ng 207 Thornburgh St.","height":"22692","width":"16616"}}
